com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.documents.sequence

Class ImmutableSequence

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.documents.sequence.SequenceCharSequence
      • com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.documents.sequence.ImmutableSequence
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    PluginDocument, SequenceDocument, XMLSerializable, XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible, CharSequence, Comparable<SequenceCharSequence>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ImmutableSequenceImplementation

    public abstract class ImmutableSequence
extends SequenceCharSequence
implements SequenceDocument
    An implementation of a SequenceDocument that is immutable and has very low memory usage. Generally it is only advantageous to use ImmutableSequences when dealing with lots of sequences. ImmutableSequences have a very low memory usage overhead per sequence, and lots of ImmutableSequences constructed with an ImmutableSequence.Builder that have names which have a common pattern will have low memory usage for storing their names.

    As of Geneious 5.0, this class is unable to store annotations and sequence descriptions but these may be supported in future versions. Data that is currently supported by this class includes

    • Sequence names
    • Sequence bases/residues
    • Leading/trailing gap lengths
    • Sequence quality (see NucleotideGraphSequenceDocument), but not chromatogram trace data)
    To construct an instance of an ImmutableSequence, use createImmutableSequence(SequenceDocument, boolean) or to achieve even lower memory usage when constructing many sequences which have a common pattern to their names, use ImmutableSequence.Builder
    Since:
    API 4.11 (Geneious 5.0)

      • insert

        public abstract ImmutableSequence insert(int index,
                       CharSequence charSequence)
        Description copied from class: SequenceCharSequence
        Creates a copy of this SequenceCharSequence with the specified CharSequence inserted at the specified index. Doesn't modify this SequenceCharSequence. The returned SequenceCharSequence will support logarithmic time insertions and deletions, and its length will be longer than this sequence's by charSequence.length().

        In order to obey the contract of SequenceCharSequence that it is immutable, the length of charSequence and the characters retured from charSequence must not change after calling this method.

        Overrides:
        insert in class SequenceCharSequence
        Parameters:
        index - The position where to insert csq. All existing characters at or to the right of this position will be moved to the right by charSequence.length().
        charSequence - A CharSequence to insert at the specified index. The length of charSequence and the characters retured from charSequence must not change after calling this method.
        Returns:
        A copy of this SequenceCharSequence with csq inserted at the specified index.

      • insertGaps

        public abstract ImmutableSequence insertGaps(int leadingGapsLength,
                           int trailingGapsLength,
                           int[] internalGapPositions,
                           int[] internalGapSizes)
        Creates a new sequence identical to this one except with some gaps inserted.
        Parameters:
        leadingGapsLength - the number of additional leading gaps to add to this sequence
        trailingGapsLength - the number of additional trailing gaps to add to this sequence
        internalGapPositions - the positions of internal gaps to insert into this sequence. All values must be in the range 1 through to the internal sequence length-1 inclusive and indicate that a gap should be inserted before the current character at that index. This array may be null which is equivalent to an empty array.
        internalGapSizes - the sizes of corresponding internal gaps to insert into this sequence. This array must be equal in length to internalGapPositions. Each size must be positive. This array may be null which is equivalent to an empty array.
        Returns:
        a new sequence identical to this one except with some gaps inserted. If this sequence is a NucleotideSequenceDocument the returned sequence will also be a NucleotideSequenceDocument. If this sequence is an AminoAcidSequenceDocument the returned sequence will also be a AminoAcidSequenceDocument

      • getCharAndQualityAtIgnoringEndGaps

        public abstract int getCharAndQualityAtIgnoringEndGaps(int characterIndex)
        Provides both the sequence character and the quality in a single method call, which is almost twice as fast as requesting the 2 values separately.
        Parameters:
        characterIndex - the index of the character to get, relative to the leadingGapsLength.
        Returns:

      • getData

        public abstract void getData(int internalStartIndex,
           int sizeOfDataToGet,
           byte[] characters,
           byte[] qualities,
           int startingOffsetIntoDataArrays)
        Provides sequence character and qualities for multiple positions in a single method call, which is much faster than requesting the values separately. This method may only be used to retrieve data that doesn't include end gap regions.
        Parameters:
        internalStartIndex - the index of the first character to get, relative to the leadingGapsLength. (e.g. 0 to get the first non-end-gap character)
        sizeOfDataToGet - the number of characters of data to get. internalStartIndex+sizeOfDataToGet must not be greater than SequenceCharSequence.getInternalSequenceLength()
        characters - an array to copy the sequence characters into.
        qualities - an optional array to copy the sequence quality into. This may be null to not retrieve quality data. If this array is not null, and this sequence has no quality, quality values of 0 will be set. If any quality values exceed 255, they will be capped at 255.
        startingOffsetIntoDataArrays - the index in 'characters' and 'qualities' to start copying data into.
